issues.body:
When parsing `salted` (`salted = salted-claim / salted-element / decoy`) in some languages, one might not have the length of the `salted-array`. It can cause the deserialization to be less efficient because the second element is either a claim key or a claim value depending if `salted` is a `salted-claim` or a `salted-element` (CDDL below for reference).

```cddl
salted-claim = [
  bstr .size 16,     ; 128-bit salt
  (int / text),      ; claim name
  any                ; claim value
]
salted-element = [
  bstr .size 16,     ; 128-bit salt
  any                ; claim value
]
```

In some languages, like in Rust, the main parsing library (serde) does only [provide an iterator](https://docs.rs/serde/latest/serde/de/trait.SeqAccess.html#method.next_element) when deserializing arrays. It also does not provide an infallible [size hint](https://docs.rs/serde/latest/serde/de/trait.SeqAccess.html#method.size_hint) of the array. Hence, implementers, have to add some performance overhead in their parser to deal with that case.

The recommendation would be to have a canonical order of these fields, so that the second element is always a claim value, i.e.
```diff
salted-claim = [
  bstr .size 16,     ; 128-bit salt
+  any                ; claim value
  (int / text),      ; claim name
-  any                ; claim value
]
```

The current implementation roughly looks like this in Rust. You have to deserialize the second element twice: first to an intermediate `Value`, then, depending on the array size, to either a claim name or value.

```rust
impl<'de, T> serde::Deserialize<'de> for Salted<T> {
    fn deserialize<D: serde::Deserializer<'de>>(deserializer: D) -> Result<Self, D::Error> {
        struct SaltedVisitor<T>(core::marker::PhantomData<T>);

        impl<'de, T> serde::de::Visitor<'de> for SaltedVisitor<T> {
            type Value = Salted<T>;

            fn expecting(&self, formatter: &mut std::fmt::Formatter) -> std::fmt::Result {
                write!(formatter, "a salted disclosure")
            }

            fn visit_seq<A: serde::de::SeqAccess<'de>>(self, mut seq: A) -> Result<Self::Value, A::Error> {
                use serde::de::Error as _;

                let salt = seq.next_element::<Salt>()??;
                let second: Option<Value> = seq.next_element::<Value>()?;
                let third: Option<T> = seq.next_element::<T>()?;

                Ok(match (salt, second, third) {
                    (salt, None, None) => Salted::Decoy(Decoy { salt: (salt,) }),
                    (salt, Some(value), None) => {
                        let value = value.deserialized()?; // <-- overhead
                        Salted::Element(SaltedElement { salt, value })
                    },
                    (salt, Some(name), Some(value)) => {
                        let name = name.deserialized()?; // <-- overhead
                        Salted::Claim(SaltedClaim { salt, value, name })
                    },
                    _ => return Err(A::Error::custom("Invalid disclosure")),
                })
            }
        }

        deserializer.deserialize_seq(SaltedVisitor(Default::default()))
    }
}
```

